  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Yongqing County
  author: Ko Cho-gi
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A path winds through the layered peaks,
    The lonely fortress leans upon the void of sky.
    The green gorge lies perpetually empty and still—
    Thin clouds drift, now present, now vanished.

    Ancient pines make their own whispered song,
    Spring birds call to each other in gentle chorus.
    All the landscape conspires to stir the poet's heart,
    And lingering here, I can only tip the wine cup again.
  footnotes:
    - The 'fortress' (城) likely refers to Yongqing County itself, perched precariously in the mountains, creating a sense of isolation and transcendence.
    - The motif of wine-tipping (倒酒壺) at the end suggests the speaker's surrender to the contemplative beauty of the place, a common trope in East Asian poetry expressing both melancholy and spiritual contentment.
